[Student "S"]
{You have 12 points which isn't quite enough to force to game.

It is just right for a limit raise though, so you bid 3\H.

Partner does bid the game.

East would play 4\H.

Click 

West plays 4\H. The defense takes the first three \S tricks, then switches to a \C.

<b>West plays 4\H. The defense takes the first three \S tricks, then switches to a \C.</b>

Losers: \S 3 : \H ?? : \D 0 : \C 0 : Total = 3+??

With no more outside losers your task is very very simple:<b>DO NOT LOSE A TRUMP TRICK</b>.

There is no problem if trumps split 2-2 or 3-1, so you can put your mind to 4-0 splits only. If North holds \H J 8 6 3 then it won't matter whether your first trump play is \HA or \HK, you will still be able to finesse the \HJ. But if South holds \H J 8 6 3 it is vital that you first play either the \HK or \HQ. If you start with the \HA you will have lost your finesse position. The general rule is to first play a high trump from the hand that has two. That preserves a finesse through either defender's \H J x x x.

Visualize the situation if your first play was the \HA. North would show out and you would learn that South held \H J 8 6 3 but you couldn't do anything about it.

Next visualize the situation if your first play was the \HK. North would show out and you would play the \HQ, then a small \H finessing your \H10. 

Finally visualize the situation if your first play was the \HK and it was South who showed out. You would play a small \H to your \HA, then lead a \H toward dummy finessing with the \H9.

Using the correct Plan guarantees the contract however \Hs split.}

